summary:
A Postgraduate from the University of Leeds, UK in Automotive Engineering with hands-on experience in the usage of 3D modelling software such as SolidWorks, CATIA and AutoCAD, also proficient in FEA Simulation packages such as ANSYS and Abaqus. 
Self-disciplined, motivated and inclined towards technical aspects of engineering

projects:
[{'title': 'Design & Analysis of a Formula Student Race car Chassis', 'date': {'start': {'month': 10, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': 12, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}}, 'description': None, 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Aravind', 'last_name': 'Prasanth', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Mechanical Designer at GustoMSC'}]}, {'title': 'Optimisation of an FSAE Race Car Powertrain (B.E. Thesis)', 'date': {'start': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}}, 'description': 'The objective was to find the optimum volume, length and diameter of the runner and the configuration of the air intake and Exhaust.
CFD simulation of an air intake, helps in measuring the velocity and pressure in the intake, but it does not indicate the improvement in the engine performance. By coupling CFD software (Ricardo VECTIS) with a 1D engine simulation software (Ricardo WAVE) the direct value of power for each design iteration can be found. Thus, enabling to explore deeper and intricate details in Air Intake systems like Helmholtz Resonators and Swirl vanes to achieve the optimal result.
The simulation of the position of the air inlet both in the straight line and while the car is turning is undertaken, it is further optimised for highest pressure at the mouth of the intake with the least impact on the aerodynamics of the car. This is followed by designing the restrictor, the plenum, and the exhaust headers. The engine model created on Ricardo Wave will gave the values for the pressure at the engine port and the inlet pressure was obtained from the CFD simulation. Finally, an Acoustic simulation was done to check the noise levels of the exhaust.
The results of the 1D/3D simulation give the optimum values for the volume, length and diameter of the runner and the configuration of the air intake and Exhaust.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Aravind', 'last_name': 'Prasanth', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Mechanical Designer at GustoMSC'}]}, {'title': 'Development of Mechanical System for an Autonomous Formula Student Car (MSc Thesis)', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'I worked on the mechanical aspects of converting a Driven Formula Student Race Car to a Driverless Car.
I designed and developed the Autonomous Braking System. The Emergency Braking System (EBS) was designed and simulated using MATLAB Simulink. The Steering force was calculated and validated using physical testing. These values were used for the selection of the motors and design of the steering components. A material selection study was performed on CES EduPack to determine the choice of material for each component based on cost, mass, strength and stiffness. Additionally, topological optimization was done on each of the components. I also performed an energy requirement study to quantify the additional energy required to power the autonomous system.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Aravind', 'last_name': 'Prasanth', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Mechanical Designer at GustoMSC'}]}]
